page.text: Parkers Convenience Store - Traffic Impact Analysis
A convenience store is proposed on the east side of Buckwalter Parkway in Bluffton. The
development is anticipated to be completed in 2011 and will consist of a convenience store with
16 fueling stations. One access is planned at an existing median break on Buckwalter Parkway,
opposite Lake Point Drive. The site location and conceptual master plan are shown in Figure 1
The scope of this study was coordinated with the Beaufort County Engineering Department. The
following intersections were identified for inclusion in the traffic study:
Buckwalter Parkway and Lake Point Drive
Buckwalter Parkway is a 4-lane median divided highway with a 45 mph speed limit. The Lake
Point Drive intersection with Buckwalter Parkway is approximately 1,600 feet south of the
intersection of Bluffton and Buckwalter Parkways. The Lake Point Drive approach to
Buckwalter Parkway is stop controlled. Right and left turn bays are provided on Buckwalter
Parkway for vehicles turning on to Lake Point Drive.
Weekday peak hour turning movement counts were taken at the Lake Point Drive intersections in
February 2010. Counts at the Buckwalter / Bluffton Parkway intersection were provided by the
County (taken in April, 2009). Intersection diagrams and the detailed count data are included in
the Appendix. Capacity analyses were completed based on the recent counts; results are shown in
Overall, the Buckwalter Parkway / Bluffton Parkway intersection is operating with minimal
delays. The Lake Point Drive approach to Buckwalter Parkway experiences some significant
delays during the peak hours, especially the left turn movement.
Parkers Convenience Store - Traffic Impact Analysis
The MUTCD defines warrant guidelines that are used to evaluate the need for traffic signals. The
eight warrants described in Section 4C of the 2009 edition of the MUTCD are used as tools to
make a determination. This warrant analysis considers Warrants 1, 2, and 3 based on the existing
conditions and the counts taken in February 2010.
Since the speed limit on Buckwalter Parkway is greater than 40 mph, the reduced warrant
thresholds (70%) are applied. The minor street right turn volumes can be applied in multiple
ways; warrants are evaluated under two scenarios. One scenario considers the right turn volume
and treats the minor approach as 2-lanes; the other scenario omits the right turn volume and treats
the minor street approach as 1-lane. The Appendix includes the details of the warrant analysis.

The analysis confirms that the intersection volumes currently satisfy the warrants established by
the MUTCD. Warrants 1, 2, and 3 are met.

Most of the trips can be considered “pass by” trips, or trips that are made as an intermediate stop
from a point of origin to a primary destination (other than this development). Pass by trips
contribute to the driveway volumes but are not added to the adjacent street traffic. Trip

To predict the future (no-build) volumes, existing traffic counts (January 2010) are raised by 5%
to account for general growth in the area.
The trips generated by the convenience store are assigned to the study intersections based on an
assumed 50%-50% north-south split. These volumes are then added to the background volumes
to determine the build out conditions.

Parkers Convenience Store - Traffic Impact Analysis
The intersection of Buckwalter Parkway and Bluffton Parkway should continue to function
Delays at the intersection of Lake Point Drive and Buckwalter Parkway, however, will continue
to grow without some type of improvement. The Parkers Convenience Store will generate
relatively minimal amounts of new traffic and would not be the root cause of delay at the
Several options for improvement are considered below.
The residents of Grande Oaks currently experience moderately long delays entering and exiting
their neighborhood, based on recent traffic counts taken. A traffic signal at Lake Point Drive and
Buckwalter Parkway could alleviate these side-street delays.
Installation would likely require coordination of the signal timing, as there would be three signals
on Buckwalter Parkway within a ½ mile (at Lake Point, Buckwalter, and Publix).
Should the Bluffton Parkway be relocated to the south and extended east as envisioned, the Lake
Point intersection would be approximately 700 feet south of the new Bluffton / Buckwalter
intersection. Two signals located at this distance are not compatible with the existing Buckwalter
Installation of a roundabout at this location could also alleviate the delays for vehicles entering
Buckwalter Parkway. Analysis using the GDOT roundabout tool (which is based on the latest
NCHRP procedures), indicates that the overall intersection could function with minimal delays if
a multi-lane roundabout were installed (based on the anticipated 2011 volumes).
As mentioned, this intersection would be approximately 700 feet south of the new Bluffton /
Buckwalter intersection if the Bluffton Parkway is relocated. If Bluffton Parkway is realigned, a
roundabout may potentially be preferable to a signal at this location, but would require further
study to evaluate how the Bluffton Parkway extension alters traffic patterns. Further analysis of
this option would be required prior to the extension. A roundabout would have greater cost and
Provide a new connection from Lake Point Drive to adjacent arterials
The addition of a new outlet for vehicles within the developments around Lake Point Drive could
also alleviate delays. An additional outlet could divert traffic and lessen the demand on the Lake
Point Drive approach to Buckwalter Parkway.
If implemented, similar connections would be recommended on the east side of Buckwalter
Parkway for any new developments surrounding the Parkers Convenience Store.
Parkers Convenience Store - Traffic Impact Analysis
A convenience store is proposed on the east side of Buckwalter Parkway, opposite Lake Point
Drive. The store should generate relatively minimal amounts of traffic.
Delays on the existing Lake Point Drive approach (eastbound) to Buckwalter Parkway are
currently at LOS F in the afternoon. With increased volumes in the area, these delays will
continue to worsen. Existing volumes at the intersection meet signal warrant thresholds. In the
short term, installation of a signal could alleviate delays on the side streets.
Several long term considerations should be examined for this intersection. If the Bluffton
Parkway is relocated to the south and extended east of Buckwalter Parkway, the new Bluffton /
Buckwalter Parkway intersection would be only 700 feet north of Long Point Drive. Based on
the recent Access Management Plan for Buckwalter Parkway, two signals cannot be located this
A multi-lane roundabout, installed at the Lake Point Drive / Buckwalter Parkway intersection
could also alleviate the existing traffic delays, based on the current volumes. If the Bluffton
Parkway is relocated, a roundabout might be preferable to a signal, but would require further
study to ensure that queues at the Bluffton / Buckwalter signal do not affect the operation of the
roundabout. A roundabout option would have a greater construction cost and additional right-of-
Adding to the connectivity of the regional roadway network could also alleviate delays,
depending on the nature of the improvements. Diverting traffic away from Lake Point Road by
means of a connection to other arterial roadways could help to lessen delays on the approach to
Buckwalter Parkway. These types of connections would obviously require coordination and
cooperation among surrounding land owners, or inclusion in the future project to realign Bluffton
If and when the Bluffton Parkway extension project is funded, options for the intersection of
Buckwalter Parkway / Lake Point Drive should be reexamined in more detail.
